	sylb:summary "Since Ukraine announced its termination of CIS (Commonwealth of Independent States) presidency in March 2014 and furthermore declared the will to withdraw its membership of the community, an ongoing process that was overshadowed by the Crimea crisis and the armed conflict in Eastern Ukraine, the relation between CIS and CEE (Central and Eastern Europe) entered the limelight of the European political discourse. A slowing down economy and stagnation in political reforms of many CIS members make the CEE model more and more appealing to some. A complex structure of influences, particular interests and historic front lines appears to be a breeding ground for radicalization and conflicts.

";
	sylb:method "Key goals of the course are to understand the historic developments and preconditions of today’s challenges in Central and Eastern Europe (CEE), being able to analyse recent conflicts and front lines and to develop a capability to identify spheres of influences and national interests.

Teaching methods are lecture, students' presentations, group work and writing essays.

";
	sylb:schedule "第1回 Introduction: CEE and CIS 
CEE (Central and Eastern Europe) and CIS Commonwealth of Independent States), political and economic issues;

第2回 The Austrian-Hungarian empire
The Austrian-Hungarian monarchy (of the 19th century) as a model of a unified Europe, the crisis of the Habsburg monarchy, the Austrian-Hungarian compromise of 1867, national subpression;

第3回 The rise of nationalism
Nationalist movements in the Austrian-Hungarian monarchy and eastern neighbour states.

第4回 World War I 
An alalysis of World War I with a special focus on Central and Eastern Europe.

第5回 Post war order in Central and Eastern Europe
The treaties of St. Germain and Versailles, the formation of the nation state in Central and Eastern Europe

第6回 World War II 
The expansion of Hitler-Germany in the east, the Hitler-Stalin pact and its impacts on the region, war crimes and Holocaust in Eastern Europe, Stalinist subpression and famines, the Yalta conference;

第7回 Cold War in Central and Eastern Europe 
The iron curtain, the communist era, Warsaw pact and Comecon, democratic and national resistance (e.g. Berlin 1953, Budapest 1956, Prague 1968, Danzig 1980), icons of the anti-communist resistance: Vaclav Havel, Wolf Biermann, Lech Walesa, etc.

第8回 The velvet revolution and the fall of the Berlin wall
The impact of Gorbachev's reform policy, the sudden downfall of the communist regimes;

第9回 Transformation 
Political and economic transformation, social issues, the dissolution of Chechoslovakia, the post-Soviet Baltic states;

第10回 Yugoslavia
Civil war in former Yugoslavia, war crimes and ethnic cleansing, refugee crisis, ideological conflicts in Western Europe regarding Yugoslavia;

第11回 European integration and NATO englargement
Political and economic spheres of influence, economic and political comparision of CEE and CIS states;

第12回 Ukraine: Between CIS and CEE
The orange revolution (2004-2005), conflict between pro-Russia and pro-Europe movements, Maidan revolte (2013-2014), Crimea crisis and civil war (since 2014).

第13回 Future Outlook 
Economic status, the effects of finance and debt crisis, relations with Russia an Russian minorities in the Baltic states, conflicts and opportunities;

第14回 Conclusions
Students' conclusions to the class

その他
Report

